---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';

const title = 'BEM vs LSCSS';
const description = 'Compare BEM and Layered Semantic CSS for naming, architecture, modifiers, state handling, scalability, and long-term maintainability.';
---

<DocsLayout
    title={title}
    description={description}
>
    <article>
        <p class="eyebrow">Comparison</p>

        <h1>
            BEM vs LSCSS
        </h1>

        <p>
            BEM helped solve real problems. It gave teams structure when CSS was
            mostly organised by panic and inheritance accidents.
        </p>

        <p>
            LSCSS keeps the useful discipline but removes the naming ceremony,
            reduces selector noise, and leans harder on cascade layers and modern
            CSS features instead of longer class names.
        </p>

        <h2>
            Main differences
        </h2>

        <ul>
            <li>BEM uses explicit block__element--modifier naming</li>
            <li>LSCSS prefers semantic component names with shallow selectors</li>
            <li>BEM often duplicates structure in class names</li>
            <li>LSCSS uses layers and scope to reduce naming pressure</li>
            <li>BEM modifiers are naming-heavy</li>
            <li>LSCSS uses clearer modifier and state classes</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>
            Where BEM works well
        </h2>

        <ul>
            <li>large teams needing strict consistency</li>
            <li>older codebases without modern CSS support</li>
            <li>systems where explicit naming reduces onboarding pain</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>
            Where LSCSS helps more
        </h2>

        <ul>
            <li>modern front-end teams using cascade layers</li>
            <li>projects focused on maintainability over naming rituals</li>
            <li>systems where state and theme handling matter heavily</li>
            <li>teams wanting less verbose HTML and CSS</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>
            Recommended reading
        </h2>

        <ul>
            <li><a href="/principles/">Core principles</a></li>
            <li><a href="/state-classes/">State classes</a></li>
            <li><a href="/theme-layer/">Theme layer</a></li>
            <li><a href="/decision-trees/">Decision trees</a></li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            BEM is not wrong. It is simply older architecture solving older
            problems. CSS has moved on. Some naming conventions forgot to.
        </p>
    </article>
</DocsLayout>
